No liberating amendment for Tymoshenko by Parliament
The Ukrainian parliament today refused to propose to abolish, as part of an amendment to the Criminal Code, the section on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko had been convicted.
The new regulation, which could have paved the way for the liberation of the imprisoned minister of ex-premier, was rejected by the Members at the second reading of the motion for a mitigating the penalties for economic offences.
Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for the conclusion of a supposedly harmful contract with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not yet final, and in December the appeal of the convicted persons will be brought before the court.
Timoshenko himself described the verdict as a political revenge of the regime and also in the West the trial caused suspicion of bias of the court.
The request to remove Section 365 from the Criminal Code on the basis of which the Minister of Execution was sentenced was supported by 147 deputies.
226 votes would have been necessary for its adoption.
