Iranian students are ready to die for their country's core program.
They formed a living shield.
A few hundred university students formed a living shield around a core object in Iran.
With this gesture, they wanted to demonstrate their support for their country's core programme before a possible Israeli attack.
The students prayed in front of the building on Tuesday noon and then announced their death to the United States and Israel.
A few hundred students from the university in Isfahan, Iran, formed a living shield around the nuclear technology center in Isfahan on Tuesday, where uranium is processed.
They wanted to make it clear that they were willing to protect their country's core programme, if necessary, with their own lives.
The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) recently stated in its report that Iran seemed to have long since abandoned its efforts to create a nuclear weapon.
In Israel, too, there is talk about a possible attack on Iranian nuclear facilities.
Students had prayed at noon in front of the entrance to the complex and then proclaimed death to the United States and Israel.
According to the Israeli press, in the event of an attack aimed at largely paralyzing Iran's nuclear program, the nuclear enrichment plant in Natan would also be targeted from the centre of Isfahan.
The menu of a fat-addicted child: it does not eat breakfast and eat sausage for dinner
More than a third of children from 9 to 13 have overweight problems, with 9 percent of all pupils and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Recent surveys have been proven - obese children mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This shows once again how important for the healthy development of a human being is the milieu in which he grows up and are the examples that surround him.
On the tables of obese children, sausages are up to half more frequently on the table than in families where normal-weight children live.
More than 19 percent of overweight children had fries for dinner on the day before the Enlightenment Action under the motto "Adiposity is no coincidence".
In families with fat children, sports are not exactly one of the favorite activities, however, the majority of today's students are also concerned - only 15 percent replied that their parents find themselves at least once a week time for active exercise.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place last year towards the end of the school year, with nearly 900 children from primary schools all over the Czech Republic surveyed.
This was already the second year of the "Adiposity is no coincidence" action, which is supported by the General Health Insurance Fund and the Unilever Society.
To date, more than 12 thousand students from 4th and 8th classes have participated in the project.
Unhealthy diet and lack of exercise in the family are decisive factors that are responsible for the frighteningly increasing number of children with overweight or even obesity.
"For example, only half of the children surveyed reported eating breakfast-second-breakfast-dinner-vesper dinner five times a day - one of the main requirements for a healthy diet," says one of the survey results.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that relative little things, such as the regular breakfast time of the family, are also important for the healthy development of a child.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of the pupils' families have breakfast.
And - in most families, everyone eats breakfast for themselves.
Worst was the finding that every tenth family does not eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast is considered the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
Among other things, the survey showed that the families of overweight children often consume unhealthy fries.
And almost everyone - regardless of their weight - drinks sweet lemonades every day (70 percent)
While more than 40 percent of the children surveyed exercise, only less than half of their parents do so - only 15 percent.
Create your own menu
Another part of the survey made it possible for selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to make their own meal schedule out of the possibilities offered according to appetite and opinion.
"What Czech children between 12 and 15 prefer in terms of nutrition is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among their favorite dishes were many pastries, meat dishes and, of course, sweets.
"Alarming is above all the great popularity of sweet lemonades", is emphasized in the final report on this survey.
At lunch, i.e. the main dish, pasta won just in front of poultry.
Pulses almost didn't like the children at all and the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes as lunch was also very low.
Towards health
At the same time, the survey also showed that children are quite willing to change their eating habits when they get the right information.
"In many cases, the control group of the survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the enlightening lecture "Adipositas is not a coincidence" showed a significant shift in preferences towards principles of healthy nutrition", the results of the project state.
This was obvious, for example, in the case of sweet sodas, where many children began to give priority to ordinary water.
The children also checked in the questionnaire much more often poultry or fish as the main dish of the day and were willing to eat less dumplings or sweet food.
Pros claim - a stylist must also be a good psychologist
