V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Review
The originally carefree journey is made by a series of completely avoidable, dilettantic errors to the routine journey to the early shift.
Although it was possible to fulfill the ambitions in large part, what good is it, if obviously no one wanted to do a little more?
Even before he came to the counters, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" aroused high expectations.
He promised to move the already year old game series "Need for Speed" again into a new dimension and in the playable demonstration examples he actually did not seem to be just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious about the fitting passages in which the main protagonist gets out of the car and continues on foot.
But as you're used to at NFS, in the end, much is different than you expected.
Sure - potentially it's quite decent arcade races, but overall the game is diminished by some unnecessary mistakes that have been present in this series for more or less a few years.
So it's actually no longer a mistake, but rather a sign of a basically incomprehensible laziness of game developers.
The adventure starts very well.
For the first time, one is introduced into history, whose main character Jack has certain problems of personal character; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, on the west coast, you sit on the steering wheel - with the task of being the first in New York.
The basic idea contains a whole series of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race will take place on a different track and that the individual stages will take place in a different, sufficiently different and interesting environment.
You don't have a moment's impression that game would always offer the same thing.
Some environments are also very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics does not exceed that of the previous parts of the series.
So nothing world-moving.
But the drive through the desert, through autumnal landscape or high up through deep snowy landscape is visually very pleasant.
Every now and then, atypical elements bring a little variety to the individual races.
In the desert, for example, one is surprised by a desert storm that severely restricts the visibility.
In the mountains, in turn, you have to be careful not to get spilled by an avalanche.
By the way, the individual races are installed quite well in a row.
Only a few, but they're enough.
For a while you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to catch up (classical race against the stopwatch), then you expect a personal duel with a single opponent.
And the police are also involved, who wants to screw up the whole thing.
A novelty is passages in which Jack leaves the car.
This is more about certain interactive animations in which Jack escapes from someone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are much less such passages in the game than one would expect (probably only three).
In the end, this is more to the advantage of the thing, because this element at least has no chance of becoming boring - it belongs in the context of the above mentioned one of the elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model moves in the footsteps of the previous parts.
That is, from today's point of view, it does not tear out trees, on the other hand, it cannot be said that it is bad.
If you're looking for realistic simulations, you have to look elsewhere.
But an action-packed racer will continue to do quite well with the local driving model, although one could find better with the competition.
Until then, everything will be fine.
Real problems do not appear until after a certain time.
In contrast to the driving model, the collision model is not quite OK.
It's hard to expect a game of this kind to calculate complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have virtually no idea of how the car behaves before impacting any object, then obviously not everything is all right.
Typical example: In the tight overtaking or passing of cars, one "strips" the other car only slightly in some places, in other, almost identical situation, however, one gets into the slingshot and turns wild pirouettes.
Or the car's gonna go to waste.
Thanks to the Restart system, it doesn't matter any more, it's annoying.
The restarts are solved in this way: if you have total damage or land far off the track, then the game throws you back to the last clue of the track.
Only - in every race you have only five restarts.
Once you've exhausted it, it's all over again.
So the restarts are more like a tool, in case something doesn't succeed, but you shouldn't rely on it.
Sometimes, however, the rest doesn't even help, so nothing else helps but to learn the critical section from the head.
It is extremely unpleasant that the same things often happen in the same places.
Some curves, for example, you have to pass through in a very specific way, otherwise you just don't fit through.
Elsewhere you always encounter "civil" cars in the same configuration at the appropriate place, whether you are first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is particularly annoying in situations when you see that the opponent is passing by two cars in front of one, but until you get there yourself, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive them around or brake them.
And it doesn't matter when you get there, because everything is designed in such a way that this situation always comes close to your nose.
The opponents have other advantages.
In the whole game there are a few places where you are always overtaken by the same opponent in the same place and here again without regard to the time.
The craziest thing is to finish the game on the long bridge that you pass in opposite direction.
The opponent must obviously get one out of here on hell.
And if he's in front of you, then of course he takes the view, so that you drive your own car there a few times in Klump.
Sure - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting but this intention is so clear that it quickly avoids the joy of the game.
And that's a pity, because despite the simpler driving model, the game is overall quite entertaining and in places also so action-packed that you almost don't know where your head is.
And in principle, it doesn't matter what is "guilty" about it - the concept with fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in such a way that no boredom can arise, or something completely different...
An unusual idea is also the change of car during the race.
One must not overlook the petrol stations on the route, because it is here that one can change the car, although in most cases the car is sufficient, which one has just.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for the urban areas, the strong American saloons for the straight highways and exotic super sports cars for the technical rides, for example on the serpentines in the mountains.
The task mode (challenges) goes hand in hand with the mode of the game history - i.e. the races in the individual locations you know from the history.
Here, there are not only medals, but also points of experience for one's own profile, which is common to the tasks (challenges) and history.
In order to get to the higher driver level, different objects have to be opened up: from the car to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is connected at the same time to the online Autolog function, which compares, among other things, its own results with those of other players and also provides for further collective functions.
One of the other incomprehensible carvings is a situation in the last race of history.
Here you come by car into a subway tunnel (because of me), where you race in the dark on the tracks for a long time (because of me).
On the speedometer there are numbers between 150 a 200 km/h (because of me), but suddenly a subway comes from behind and drives you uncompromisingly to scrap.
In our editorial office we will probably argue for a long time about whether this was a blackout of the game designers or whether the authors think we are so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the visual overall impression is in most cases quite appealing and here and there even brilliant.
All the more annoying is that in some exciting moments the refresh rate slows down and this is sometimes quite dramatic.
However, this is particularly true of accidents involving a larger number of participants, where a continuous FPS is of no use anyway.
The sound reproduction is OK and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to reach a scale as wide as possible rather young audiences, a soundtrack was created a lá "something from everyone" - but who buys such a game because of the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run? Feelings are rather mixed.
If the game weren't reduced by the mentioned totally unnecessary mistakes, we could have asserted with the chest tone that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But that's how the game seems somehow unfinished.
In itself a great pleasure, but you should be prepared to see these mistakes with the power of airport lights.
Concert of the "Students of the Velvet Revolution" with singing ensembles of the Karlsuniversität
For the third time now, Festa Academica has offered the opportunity to combine World Student Day with the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution and this with music experience.
In the course of the festival present themselves to the twenty specialist and university choirs.
The festival focuses on the two concerts that will take place on November 17th.
"Charles University has a large share of the festival."
"Among the participants is also the choir of the Faculty of Education and the Faculty of Humanistic Studies, and the Festival Committee includes the rector Václav Hampl," said Jakub Čaloun, head of the organisational team.
The festival's absolute highlight is the public concert by Fachschulchörer, which will take place on 17 November from 2 p.m. on the square in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The program includes the composition of the famous Czech jazz musician Karel Růžička "Celebration Jazz Mass".
In the evenings the concert "Students of the Velvet Revolution" (Student Sametu) takes place in the gala rooms of the Volkshaus in Vinohrady, in which also university choirs perform, choirs of the Charles University are not excluded.
Festa Academica sets itself the goal of not only celebrating World Student Day worthy and commemorating the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but of presenting choral music at the highest level to the public and promoting creative cooperation between young people.
The main organiser is the Association of Czech Choirs in cooperation with Johannes Kepler Gymnasium.
Bohuslav Svoboda, Lord Mayor of Prague and Václav Hampl, Rector of Charles University, took over the patronage of the entire event.
The festival will take place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and Pardubice.
In addition to festive concerts, the schedule also includes numerous music meetings, student Happanings, Matinees and other events.
Detailed information can be found on the website of the festival www.festaacademica.cz
EU Ambassador Vicenová:
The Czechs have the reputation of negativeists and Eurosceptics
"The Treaty of Lisbon has brought the balance between the various institutions out of hand."
I didn't expect such a hard war to burn."
"It will take five or six years for the waves to smooth down and everyone to get used to their new role," Milena Vicenová, the Czech ambassador to the European Union, started her lecture at the Faculty of Law.
In the first part of her lecture, she showed how seriously she takes the motto "understandable and open about Europe", in which she managed to describe the individual institutions of the EU and their mutual relations in such a manageable and understandable way that she could have envied so many lecturers of the Faculty of Law of the Charles University.
Ms Vicenová also praised the new permanent chairman of the Council of Europe Herman Van Rompuy:
"At first, criticism became loud that he was too inconspicuous - a grey official who couldn't stand such a role, but I have to say that it took everyone's breath to see how well he took care of the matter.
"He is a person who is able to listen patiently to twenty-seven member states, to communicate with them and, above all, to have clear ideas about how to continue with the EU.
She then explained the new position of the High Representative for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy as an answer to the question: Who is this actually - the European Union? What number should I call?", as an important step towards the unification and better legibility of EU policy towards states, such as China or India.
No one wants to ban our oil-suppliers Quargel
Ms Vicenová also devoted herself to the agenda according to which the European Union lived, lived and intended to live in the near future.
The Czech Presidency of two years ago described it as a success.
The Czechs have mastered the financial crisis and the gas crisis and have also organised the Eastern Partnership Summit.
The case of the government during the Presidency was described as a great negative, which had seriously damaged the image of the Czech Republic.
Czech representation in the EU is currently busy.
In the words of the Ambassador, not only the Presidency, but also the subsequent crisis, which has not yet been overcome, was rather hectic.
And the EU's seven-year budget needs to be approved, which makes things much more complicated precisely because of today's economic situation.
Whether it will be a lean and economical budget, which sectors will be given priority, which countries will be more and which will be less supported - all this is now on the agenda.
The ambassador also reminds us of her own slogans that she came to Brussels: "Understandable about Europe".
"If I don't like something, it's greyish abbreviations, foreign words and jargon that nobody understands.
How am I supposed to know, as a citizen, whether they really are crooked or round cucumbers and bananas of different sizes in Brussels, or whether someone really wants to ban us from the quarries?
She would also have liked to use the EU's soil to get more Czechs into European institutions.
Europe of two or different speeds in prospect
According to the EU ambassador, the Czechs have a reputation for being Eurosceptics who perceive the negative side of the matter more than the positive side of the matter.
The weak representation of Czechs in European institutions is all the more annoying.
Many factors are to blame, including the restraint of our candidates, their inability to write motivational letters and, last but not least, the weak support of the Czech side.
In addition to the successful Czech Presidency, she also highlighted the strength and cooperation of the Visegrad Group, the so-called V4.
"Believe me, if a pole or Hungarian comes to me and there's a Slovak nearby, then the Frenchman next to me says, "Hey, what do you put your heads together - is that your V4 again?" and at the same time makes a pretty sour face.
According to Mrs Vicenové, the EU is expecting tough rules for Member States' budget policies in the future.
It sees the concept of a Europe of two or even different speeds as much more realistic than a "European federation".
"Here we have the countries of the eurozone and the countries outside the eurozone.
"We have the Schengen area and we already have the Institute of enhanced cooperation."
"For the first time it was said that only the countries that want it and those who don't want it should stand quietly away."
"There will be more and more such institutions, which ultimately amounts to a strong "Europe of different speeds", Ms Vicenová expects.
In this respect, it also commended the role of the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuyes in enforcing the principle that all issues affecting the EU as a whole must be discussed by all member states and not only by the eurozone countries.
