Innovator IBM enters the second century of its existence
If you wanted to search for a suitable word that characterizes IBM's strategy most accurately, then this would probably be the word "longevity".
For the general public, IBM is synonymous with technological revolution; it is known as a modern company, although a century has elapsed since it was founded.
The basis for this longevity was already laid by her first boss - the visionary Thomas J. Watson sen.
He already spoke of the slogan that countless worldwide problems could easily be solved if people were willing to think a little bit.
His slogan "Think!" became a trademark for the future giant's life (and, at the same time, the title of the company's internal magazine, which IBM began publishing in 1935).
This was also the basis of Watsen's thoroughly prepared corporate culture.
"For us from IBM, this long-term thinking means a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and was successful for an entire century because it remained true to its principles and did not shy away from changing everything else around.
This allowed us to transform technologies, business and also society over the course of our first century.
We hope that we will create even more in the next hundred years," said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company's current director on the occasion of the anniversary.
Well-thought-out system
In the 1930s, Watson was already working on social care for his employees - in a way similar to that of the entrepreneur Baťa in Czechoslovakia: the IBM people had as one of the first American employees paid vacations, an insurance by the entrepreneur plus elegant uniforms as workwear and a well-thought-out pay system for the best newcomers and traders.
IBM's long-term relationships with its customers are equally sophisticated.
From the very beginning, the company was brilliant in promoting talent - as one of the first companies in the world, IBM picked up any discrimination - and was able to choose accordingly.
In line with this anti-discrimination strategy is also the current plan that Palmisan will replace at the head of IBM next year by a woman - Virginia Rometty.
She has been with IBM for thirty years, so far she has taken the position of Head of Sales, Marketing and Strategy.
IBM has been making so-called online brainstormings in recent years, from which many future strategies and innovations emerge.
No wonder - there are enough ideas, almost half a million people are employed in the company.
An institution with a good reputation
Their unshakable position in business guarantees the company a strong image, both internally and externally.
"From the beginning, IBM had the concept of an institution rather than a mere technology company," said Economist professor of Harvard Business School and author of a book about IBM, Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
"IBM is not a technology company, but a company that helps solve business problems with the help of technologies," added George Colony from consulting firm Forrester Research.
As the company itself stresses, it is a difference to be only present in the market or to shape it directly through this presence.
IBM - called "Big Blue" in the states of its logo because of its family, has grown into one of the largest companies in the world in a century.
It is one of the most versatile technology companies ever - IBM develops hardware and software, infrastructures, hosting and consulting services in an incredible product range - from servers to nanotechnology.
IBM owns the most patents of all American technology companies and five of its employees have already been awarded the Nobel Prize.
His most well-known inventions include ATMs, credit cards, financial swaps, barcodes or the floppy diskette.
With approximately $220 billion in market value (market capitalization), IBM was the second-largest technology company this year (just after Apple), and for the first time since 1996 it overtook Microsoft.
Looking ahead
Not all products and innovations met the tastes of today's customers - unfortunate were, for example, the attempt with the own OS/2 operating system, the online service Prodigy or even the computers IBM PC Jr.
"Business is based on forward movement, so you cannot emotionally tie yourself to the past," says Samuel J. Palmisano.
That's why IBM has no problem building its foundations on different platforms - and if they don't work, leaving them again.
In contrast to the opponent Microsoft, which basically stands and falls with its operating system Windows.
Promising technologies
IBM's profits are largely driven by services, software and hardware, each accounting for one fifth.
In 1990, hardware with a share of more than 50 per cent was the most represented.
Since 2000, IBM has sold little profit-absorbing assets worth $15 billion, but at the same time invested $58 billion in the purchase of promising technologies.
In these investments, IBM continues after 2008, when the modern financial crisis swept the world for the first time like a storm.
Here, too, IBM remained faithful to the legacy of its first boss Thomas J. Watson, who increased his investment volume in the middle of the great global economic crisis.
So far, it seems that IBM survives today's crisis unscathed.
The value of IBM shares has increased by 120 percent since 2008 and the company's net profit continues to grow.
IBM's corporate slogan is: everything can be changed - only the values can't be changed.
This is also why it can be expected that this flexible giant will also master the next crisis.
IBM history: From cheese cutters to world flights
The company IBM (International Business Machines), founded in New York a hundred years ago, initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM only in 1924 - originally it was a brand name for a branch office in Canada and South America.
The foundation stone for IBM was the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 80s of the 19th century.
They had technologies such as the famous card clocks to register the start and end of work.
Charles Ranlett Flint became the architect of this new company, who also served as Chairman of the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the head of the competitor Thomas J. Watson to help him manage the company.
This leader shadowed even IBM's founders - Watson's ideas are still based on the company's invincible culture and identity.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began with the production and distribution of all possible machines for the trade - from sausage and cheese cutters, to cash registers.
In the first four decades of Watson's leadership, he doubled its sales to nine million dollars, and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the head chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his direction, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM technicians and computers helped guide NASA's flights into space - Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969, the man's famous flight to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC that defined the computer standard of that time came on the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it bought the consultant part of PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus fully entered the business of consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the past three years is the concept of "Smart Planet".
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in areas not even planned so far, e.g. in order to improve the situation in transport and in urban administration.
In the retail sector, IBM recently introduced the Smart Commerce platform to help traders manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
As early as 1932 IBM founded a branch in Czechoslovakia - as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe at all.
Today, IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague and here is also a top research team of world-level that deals with the technology of voice recognition.
