Evolution of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five approved state travel agencies in the then ČSSR: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At that time the travel agencies sold mainly only trips to the socialist Eastern Bloc countries, in the West only chosen ones were allowed at that time.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania on the Black Sea and to Hungary on the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore the journeys to Yugoslavia were severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that not even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovaks) were allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a ČSSR citizen wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Even then, the travel agencies also offered trips to the West, but then you had to accept huge queues or stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, the thing had not yet worked out.
The so-called foreign exchange pledge - the condition for an exit to the West - was granted only "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible to find the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a trip to the West without a commitment to foreign exchange.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holidays domestically, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend homes and datschen - a habit that continues to this day.
The velvet revolution of 1989 was followed by a travel revolution of the Czechs.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries all over the world.
A huge paradox that is no longer known today is the fact that one could not travel to the currently most popular holiday country of the Czech - Croatia until 1989, because it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 90s of the last century, foreign exchange obligations were lifted in neighbouring Western European countries, which caused a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of their trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
So the Czech holidaymakers slept in the park tent when travelling to Paris, because who would have had the money for accommodation in the hotel or in a pension back then?
A typical feature of trips abroad by Czechs at that time was a luggage compartment packed with canned, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our level of life and thus also the average salaries increased, which led to another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies began to prepare regularly after 1997 for charter flights, which, thanks to the ability to negotiate volume discounts, made air travel incredibly cheaper compared to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the United States, already had foreignless payments with all the highly developed countries of the world, making travelling even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-official" travel came in 2000, when, thanks to the high demand, the first direct charter flight to an exotic country was handled - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying to distant sunny countries every year; this year, twelve exotic destinations are coming directly from the Czech Republic.
Every year, the 100 thousand Czechs travel to exotic countries!
Another important moment in the epoch that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, which definitely included our country among the world's advanced countries.
In 2008, for the first time, the Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, they spent more than CZK 15 thousand per capita for a single holiday stay, including the costs at the resort.
The general meeting is to find a new chairman - again a stalemate threatens.
For almost five months, Czech football has no chairman, threatening that Ivan Hašek's successor at the head of the Czech Football Association (FAČR) will not be known even after the extraordinary general meeting on Thursday in Nymburk.
To date, there has been no agreement as to which electoral system is to be elected.
Without these, no vote on the three potential successors is possible at all.
Three interested parties want to manage Czech football - Jindřich Rajchl, Miroslav Pelta and Tomáš Paclík.
In June, Hašek resigned from his role, inviting his colleagues to agree and find a strong personality that could lead football in the future.
Only - in the era after Hašek the old querels broke out again between the two chambers of association, which cannot agree on a common candidate.
This was clear and clear on 16 September when the new president was to be selected.
The delegates of the Annual General Meeting had come to the People's House in the Smíchov district of Prague for nothing, because the negotiations had no result and this was not just about the election itself.
One could not even agree on who is actually entitled to vote at the plenary assembly - only the statutory representatives or also the functionaries endowed with a power of attorney.
On this single point, agreement was reached at least in part, to which the recommendation of the Institute for State and Law contributed, whose opinion was that representation on a proxy basis was not acceptable.
However, disputes over the electoral order continue.
The Executive Committee also no longer clarified the matter, at which meetings - whether ordinary or extraordinary - in principle nothing else is on the agenda.
Even if the views on the election changed a few times - the neuralgic point remained the same.
The question is: how to proceed in the third round to avoid a stalemate situation?
"The issue is whether to proceed in accordance with the statutes or whether to find a completely different model," said Dušan Svoboda, one of the three vice-chairmen of the FAČR, who represents professional football in management.
According to the statutory model, in the third round, the candidate who receives the greater percentage support in the Chamber for which he is running wins.
Moravia is supposedly willing to compromise on the fact that the candidate who receives the higher number of votes from both chambers wins.
The Czech side in turn insists on the condition that the winner receives at least a two-thirds majority in this percentage vote counting.
"Then the two preliminary rounds no longer have any meaning at all, this mode would call into question the entire bicameral concept," Svoboda understands the objections of the Moravian side, which would like it best not to bend the electoral order, but to vote according to valid statutes.
Surprisingly, Tomáš Paclík agrees with this, even though it is clear that the statutory electoral order is best suited to Pelta by all candidates.
"My wish is to be elected as far as possible according to the statutes."
"So that no nonsense substitutes are devised, as at the last general meeting," explained the owner (of the football club) Victoria Plzeň, who ran for the first time and distinguished himself from Pelta in his statements.
But Pelta remains optimistic.
In his opinion, the new chairman will be known in Nymburk and he believes that the candidates will also work constructively together in the future.
"The potential qualification of the national football team for the European Football Championship today would certainly help to calm the moods."
