Europe's most beautiful pools
Jump into the blue
By Julia Stanek
Paddling pool in Ufo-Optik, magnificent pools in Budapest: If you travel through Europe, you can experience your blue miracle - and after a city tour or a hike, you can rest your tired legs in bubble baths.
A book shows where wellness is most beautiful in the water.
When Iris Meder went on a research trip over the past one and a half years, one could not be missing in her luggage: her bathing suit.
Lying on the water at the back, she looked high in elaborately designed domes, swam towards marble putties waiting for her at the edge of the pool, and marveled at meticulously restored Art Nouveau swimming halls.
If she liked a bath, she took it flying into her notebook - with some interesting details about the building's construction and history.
More than 200 swimming pools explored architecture historian Meder in this way - and now presents her in her recently published book "Badefreuden": Volksschwimmhallen in Munich, historic bath palaces in the Black Forest, "Hardcore concrete buildings" in the Taunus.
Through 13 countries she led her "journey to the most extraordinary baths in Central Europe": In addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and one city in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old German is a true swim culture enthusiast.
She doesn't have much to do with sports, says Meder - it's different only in the water.
Annoyingly, swim fans have to deal with blue tiles and chlorine stench, while joggers can inhale the beguiling scent of spruce forests or listen to cheerful bird chirping in the park.
"One day I wondered why swimming pools must always be so ugly," says the Vienna-based Meder.
"So I started collecting beautiful baths."
Water surface doubles architecture
Splatter in the diving pool and essential sauna oils - the wellness factor in baths is so great because all senses are served, says Meder.
And if the builders have bothered themselves, swimming pools can be a real feast for the eyes: "Instead of a floor, you have a water surface in baths."
"It is transparent on the one hand, but on the other hand it reflects the beauty of the whole building."
Everything doubles visually: high vaults, colorful tiles, springboards.
The small-format picture book "Badefreuden" conveys on 190 pages interesting information about the architectural and cultural history of historical wellness oases - but above all makes a desire for a leap into the blue.
Remarkable specimens were discovered by pool collector Meder during her research in Hungary.
In addition to magnificent spas such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi bath in Budapest, it found a nitrate-containing water in a rustic karst cave (cave bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) as well as a thermal bath, whose basins are filled with alkaline water and are located in a bottle-shaped building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény).
Spectacular views, on the other hand, offer many heated outdoor pools in Switzerland and Austria: while you have the whole city in mind from the Zurich rooftop pool, you can see the snow-covered Arlberg in the outdoor pool of a bath in St. Anton - and: In the steam room there is a window from which you can observe the hustle and bustle on the ski slope.
Perhaps the most extraordinary pool design awaits bathers in Längenfeld: The Aquadome Ötztal looks like a UFO just landed in the Alps.
It steams from three shells open upwards in winter, while in the background the mountains of the Ötztal rise into the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not in every swimming pool the pool collector Meder got the smell of chlorine in the nose.
Many thermal baths smell of sulfur, in the Árpád bath in the Hungarian Békescsaba it smells so strongly of heating oil that you hardly think you have landed in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkali-hydrogen carbonate-containing medicinal water, which is almost black and its mud sticks to the skin as soon as you slip into the pool - a wellness experience of a special kind.
In one place, however, Iris Meder was disappointed in her search for beautiful bathing places: when she wanted to visit the outdoor and sunbathing in the Czech bath Luhatschowitz, she found a closed terrain.
The bathroom, designed by architect Dušan Jurkovic in 1902, has now been closed.
When Meder took a look through the weathered windows of the red-white-yellow Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds growing between the tiles.
In contrast, one has counteracted the decline in a magical swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
Three phases of construction have already passed this bath; one can discover not only neo-Romanesque elements, which date from the time of its construction in 1844, but also a Moorish hall in the Alhambra style, which was added around 1900.
Since the careful modernization in 1995, the Palais Thermal has been the favourite pool of pool connoisseur Iris Meder - not only because it was originally from the Black Forest.
"It is already an achievement to merge such different architectural styles into such a great unit," says Meder.
With such a palace the dive in the thermal pool is obviously only a minor thing.
