21er Haus in Vienna
The Moved Pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with ups, downs and happy endings: The Austrian World Exhibition Pavilion of Brussels won prizes in 1958, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and decayed.
Now it is reopened as an exhibition house.
If modern post-war architecture is swarmed with clear shapes, glass halls, bold turns and new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion by architect Karl Tailfer is an apt and famous example for the 1958 Brüssler World Exhibition.
Dicker's pavilion was awarded the Grand Prix d'Architecture for its light and floating steel-glass construction.
The building is still considered a milestone of contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so famous that he also built the pavilion at the next World Exhibition in Austria.
With his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus a bowl-like side building in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion, planned as a temporary exhibition building, was erected after the world exhibition in the Swiss garden at the Vienna Südbahnhof, rebuilt and opened a museum of the 20th century in 1962 - the "20s Haus" was called it.
However, the building was neither spatially nor technically suitable as a museum - no walls for hanging art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art in Vienna got a new house.
Since 2001, the building was empty and came down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21er Haus" and will be used in the future as a museum of contemporary art.
Tuesday evening, the Belvedere Museum, to which the house belongs, opens the first exhibition - a stroke of luck in every respect.
The new beginning was accomplished by Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, art historian with a considerable career, among others in youth as a figure skater, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, strongly implemented the conversion with politicians and monument protectors, she procured public funds and private sponsorship funds and determined the use.
Apart from contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the eponymous foundation, there was to be a café and a bookstore, and an office building had to be built for this purpose.
Strict supervision, small budget
For the implementation Krischanitz was then the ideal occupation.
Not only because he had carefully rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich's Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied at the Technical University of Vienna at Dicker and the pavilion was for him a "very important place" where he had looked at the exhibitions "almost every weekend".
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which was already lost in generosity and ease when he moved to Vienna and its conversion.
In the current reconstruction, there were far bigger problems: the building was "an energy hurler," says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass façade were replaced, glass fibre reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold bridges steel beams have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been renovated.
Two basements brought space for the new use, a lowered light pit between house and street ensures the exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light tail pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in the old reddish brown rust protection shade.
And the theater is even exactly the same as it used to be.
And all this under strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small budget.
"Often a material had to be found which is good and cheap and also liked the monument protection office," says Krischanitz and points to a rough ground in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and modifications, the building has remained flexible and light.
It was difficult with the pavilion "that came from Brussels", Krischanitz recently said, a typical "drop-in-the-city story".
Such an architecture stands "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "awaken a real consciousness".
In this case, however, the 21 house is not in the wrong place, because there has been a stroke of urban planning: around the Swiss garden the completely new planned "Hauptbahnhofsquartier" with office and residential buildings is being created.
