Although Breivik may have acted alone, he is far from alone in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time before his attack in front of his computer and chatted with some of the millions of nationalists who support extreme right-wing groups on social networks.
After the tragedy this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
That's easy - you just have to log on to Facebook.
"We found that it was not difficult to come to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the main author of a recent report by the British ideas factory DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook's hideout of personal data is so encyclopaedic, Bartlett says that researchers simply have to use the site's advertising tool to accurately define their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy - just as marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of far-right groups across Europe and then turned them into add-ups, but instead of linking to a new band or diet product, the Adds invited users to a survey asking for their level of education, their attitude towards violence and their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 supporters of 14 extremely right-wing parties in 11 European countries - without even having to leave their office once.
"It's a quite new research method," says Bartlett.
Some of the results hardly surprise. Online promoters of right-wing extreme groups are mostly young, male and are angry about immigration.
But in a sort of surprising twist, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more rational, democratic and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screens."
DEMO's work is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Ideas factories, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything, from health issues to social trends such as "Likes", text messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three content per day, Facebook's "Data Supernova" generates a research boom that has increased the number of scientific papers with the name of this page in the title by nearly 800 percent over the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that you can study through this site people you don't normally reach with your clipboard on the street.
"If you used to try to question people of the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"They had to inform the party first and they would never have allowed them access," Bartlett says.
"On Facebook, all this falls away - you go straight to them."
Others say that the site offers an opportunity to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues has found that students who discussed their buzz on Facebook are significantly more prone to drinking problems than students who were silent about this topic.
