How to Unmask a Lie
A look at the current headlines shows how worrying and widespread deception and lies are in daily life.
The Republican presidential candidate, Herman Cain, is busy mastering the accusations of sexual harassment on the part of several women. Both sides accuse each other of lying.
Penn State's leadership is accused of perjury, as reportedly reports have been held back that a retired football coach has sexually abused boys.
Last week, an open microphone was heard when French President Nikolas Sarkozy told American President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weidner made a fool of himself when he circulated denials that were quickly refuted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards is accused of violations of campaign financing related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And then, of course, no one who has experienced it forgets the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered when he lied about his sexual relationship with Monica Levinsky during his second term at the Oval Office.
Stories about cheating at school and college exams are widespread.
There have been incidents in which teachers have given their students the answers to the exams so that they themselves were well represented in their performance reviews.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lies and cheating are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
Studies show that every day we lie between 10 and 200 times.
Many of these lies, however, are considered to be lies of necessity.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Recognizing lies or "discovering lies" is one that is important to learn for every person, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from a social game such as Scharaden, in which the goal is to call "Have a say!", decloaking a deception is a serious field of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that carried out far-reaching research projects, especially in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most of the ancient myths about lying have been unmasked.
Lies look you in the eye.
They stutter, stammer, blush, and do not always tremble.
From this one must not conclude, however, that these liars are difficult to uncover and unmask.
A trained lie-discoverer can permeate the truth by learning about the structure of the claim, the fine facial expressions, the questioning and timing.
I have spent several years studying the scientific results of the comprehensive and ever-growing area of decloaking, and it is clear that decloaking a deception is a modern ability that is easy to learn and helps us to find justice in our complex world, especially when hiring or questioning persons or negotiations or administration is one of our own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at estimating other people, raising their interest and mastering their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how they are perceived by others.
Thanks to research, we know that extroverted people lie more often than introverted people, that men are more often "self-oriented" lies than women whose lies are more "orienting themselves to others" - usually they want to protect the feelings of others - that married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are usually "fat lies").
We also know that when a person has been exposed as an evildoer, others feel less guilty of lying to that person.
How can you tell if someone's lying?
First, by observing the normal behavior of this person.
It's called "baselining," the starting position.
It provides a reference point for the later evaluation of changes.
Watch the posture, the laughter, the voice quality of your subject.
You should know better when someone normally is constantly tripping with your foot, so they don't blame him wrongly when he is tripping with his foot during a meeting.
Then pay attention to accumulations of conspicuous verbal and nonverbal behaviors.
Consider these accumulations as alarm bells that shrill, not as evidence of a decloaking.
People who are deceiving may freeze when they try to remember their story. Perhaps their feet point towards the door or they lean towards the exit, change their position in a significant way or show a "relax after the interview", this deep, relaxing exhalation and the change in posture when all the hard questions are over.
The questioners often falsely signal that a job interview is over just to look for that relaxation after the job interview.
Also pay attention to the language of your subject.
The slipper of Scott Peterson is famous when he used the past form when he claimed that his dead wife was still alive and triggered a national search for her.
Deceptive persons can also use a distancing language: "I had no sexual relationship with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or if you repeat a tricky question as a whole.
The most common verbal signs are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when they answer a tricky question: "Well... to tell you the truth ... as far as I know ... to the best of my knowledge and conscience."
This makes the answer more perceptive than objective, which often makes the alarm bells shrill.
There is no magic device for decloaking lies, but you can learn skills that make it possible to decloak.
Thanks to these skills, everyone can become less likely to be the victim of fraud, both in private and in professional life.
