Climatic adversities slowed down the economy
In the first year Mario López Valdez joined the government, unemployment and undeclared work rose in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in Sinaloa's economic history. It is the first year that Mario López Valdez, who describes himself as the initiator of change and raised great hopes for economic growth, is in government. However, due to the climatic adversities, growth cannot be mentioned, but on the contrary, the main economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused losses of millions in agriculture, but also narrowed the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first quarter.This is mainly due to the historical reduction in agricultural development of 31.16 percent, which slowed down further economic sectors.
According to a report published by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development) on the effects of frost, 582 000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, 78.03 percent of which were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent partially destroyed.
The decline in economic activity until November has led to a steady rise in unemployment in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter, because from January to March, 55 053 inhabitants of Sinaloas had no employment, which corresponds to 4.53 percent of the working population. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28% and from July to September to 6.19%, resulting in 74,000 unemployed in Sinaloa. That is 18 969 people more than in the first quarter.
Lower liquidity
The unemployment in Sinaloa that year is due to several factors. The economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), comments that the policies of public institutions indirectly declare the growing unemployment.
"What we are witnessing today is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors. Amongst other things, liquidity losses in the market due to the cuts in funding by the legislation passed to combat money laundering in Congress, because it is not easy for those who illegally accumulate dollars to let them work for themselves, invest them or use them for anything else," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the country looking for work abroad, especially in the United States, has declined, due on the one hand to entry problems and, on the other hand, because it is also difficult to find work there. These people stay here and are looking for work, which makes unemployment rise," he says.
Undeclared work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious if one takes into account the high proportion of undeclared work, which according to INEGI comprises 60.38 percent of the country's employees who work without being paid into the social security funds.
Unemployment and undeclared work are the lowest wages in Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Security Institute) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (National Agency for Labour and Social Welfare in Mexico).
The average monthly income of employees in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos until September, much less than the general government average of 7375 pesos.
Decrease in FDI
In addition to reducing economic activity and increasing unemployment, 2011 saw the largest decline in foreign direct investment (ADI) over the last ten years. According to Secretaría de Economía (State Economic Authority), the ADI amounted to 630 597 dollars from January to June, representing a decline of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 143 312 dollars in the same period last year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Agency for Economic Development) for its part has a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
Debt
In view of the economic crisis, the state government requested a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos at the National Congress in July to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities in order to reactivate the economy. The state congress approved an amount of 200 600 000 pesos, but no positive effects of the debt on any of the economic sectors in the country could be detected by November.
Reactions
The first year of the government, Mario López Valdé's incapacity for government, was evident to the representatives of the business community.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (National Chamber of Manufacturing Industry in Mexico), said that no efforts were made in 2011 to harmonise the views of the different sectors, including the state government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa was very poor this year. It has to be worked hard to regain the ground lost this year and in 2012 we have to double our efforts. The efforts of all and, in particular, the progress of the already well coordinated government team have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year made the country's economic development more difficult and slowed down.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including frost. One of the most important effects is a slowed economy that is not sufficiently moving to generate an economic dynamic that could generate an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. That's why we will complete the year well below our expectations," he said.
Redefine appeal
Teodoro Salazar Urirarte, Chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana, Sinaloa, stated that it was necessary to induce the state to more dynamic productive activities.
"We have generally observed that work has been done. We believe it is necessary to develop a long-term program to redefine the country's economic vocation and line, because it is important to activate all the material and human resources of Sinaloa," he said.
There's a lot to do
Coparmex's chairman stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that will guide the government's efforts in a better way.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current state power had made progress with the government.
"There are areas in which one can say that the government has acted more comprehensively. What I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
