The court approved for 2015 the transition to digital television in Mexico
In recent years, the switch from analogue to digital signals has been one of the most important changes in the world.
The Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) rejected the constitutional actions filed by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the Presidential Decree, and by virtue of which the switch from analogue to digital signals from 2021 to 2015 must be brought forward, due to a lack of eight votes required to contest the law.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his responsibilities when he issued the Decree-Law detailing the switch to terrestrial digital television.
This decision rejected the constitutional dispute initiated by the Senate because it did not receive the required qualified majority of eight votes so that the court could decide on constitutionality or non-constitutionality. Thus, the law remains in force.
In the project for the complaint prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, it was proposed that the Decree-Law be declared unconstitutional, since the regulations concerning radio and television are the responsibility of the Comisión Federal de Telecomunicaciones (Cofetel) (Federal Telecommunications Commission in Mexico), which is why the Decree-Law would contradict the hierarchical principles and the provisions of the law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted for the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies filed constitutional complaints against the Legislative Decree. Following the adoption of the lawsuits, Minister Sánchez Cordero no longer applied the Legislative Decree and ceased all activities to establish digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the appeal filed by the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the debate on the project, for which Minister Sánchez Cordero was also responsible.
In his contribution, the Prime Minister stated that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the country government should not regulate the measures that the public administration should take with general rules.
"I also do not believe that, if we did, the independence of the regulatory body would be compromised." She also pointed out that the central government is responsible for planning strategic policies, such as telecommunications, for constitutional reasons, because it heads state affairs.
Replacing analogue signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes that have taken place in recent years around the world, and it results in better use of the radioelectric spectrum, increased signal quality and more channels.
The postponement of the changeover, she said, was a postponement of the use of digitalisation, which was a decision in the public interest, which had not only technical aspects, "because it covered economic, social, political and security aspects."
These matters, she stressed, "required the action of the entire system, according to the principle of economic governance by the state, they included a group of features that put the Constitution into the hands of the central government."
It recalled that many countries around the world had already implemented the digital changeover, through the government, although they had highly specialised facilities.
One could not conclude that the government intervenes in the competences of Congress by issuing the contested legislative decree, because the laws passed by the legislature would be respected," she assured.
The possibility of counting the ballot papers individually in Michoacán is considered
According to PREP, the difference between first and second place in the Governor's election is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
The possibility of individual counting of ballot papers is a reality in the elections in Michoacán this year, because according to the data issued by the Programa de Resultados Electorales Preliminares (PREP), the difference between first and second place in the governorial elections is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
In this spirit, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just last November 9 the electoral office had adopted a series of regulations to harmonise local regulations with the reforms of the federal states in electoral matters.
It should be recalled that Michoacán had neither adapted his political constitution nor his electoral law nor his law on electoral justice to the reforms adopted by Congress, so that they did not enter into force during this election round. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided their publication in the State Scoreboard within the time limits provided for it with the argument that he did not object.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) ruled on the constitutional lawsuit filed by the local legislature and judged the Ombudsman's vote on the constitutional reforms to be "invalid and illegal" because it did not have the right to "determine or veto it".
María de los Ángeles Llanderal, in an interview on the possibility of individual counting of votes, stated that, thanks to the adoption of the guidelines by the Consejo General del IEM, there was now the possibility that the local electoral authority could count the ballots in part or in full.
Thus, under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may be counted in part.The results in the minutes do not agree; the record of counting and calculating the votes is not available on file or it is not in the possession of the chairman of the election committee or there are obvious errors or amendments in the minutes.
Furthermore, if there is a difference between the alleged winner and the winner in second place, which is equal to or less than one percent, the total counting of the fully completed ballots may be made, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an explicit request from the party or coalition chairman, who is the second of the above-mentioned candidates.
The total number of votes may also be counted if, after completion of the ordinary calculation, it is established that the difference between the alleged winner and the candidate in second place is equal or lower than one per cent, provided that an explicit request is made by a representative of the party whose candidate has become second. In this case, the electoral packages suspended from a partial counting would be excluded.
It is worth mentioning that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation where, according to PREP, the difference between first and second place is almost 0.16 percent, although the votes of 129 out of a total of 923 electoral protocols have not yet been counted.
