The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present to him the new government to stand up for the crisis that has led Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
A communication from the presidential palace announced that the Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with the President, Giorgio Napolitano, on Wednesday to confirm the formation of the government.
It is assumed that he will introduce a majority of technocrats to a cabinet, although it is not yet clear when the new Prime Minister will take office.
Monti said that he would present the President with the results of the talks with political parties on the formation of government.
"I want to reaffirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to cope with these difficult times," the former Commissioner told journalists.
Monti did not explicitly confirm the formation of the government, but his comments show that the obstacles have been overcome.
The "frame is now well laid out," he added.
Monti has managed to form a government in less than three days, which is much less time than normal, while Italy is fighting against a political and financial crisis that has driven the cost of debt to an unbearable level.
The new government, led by former EU Commissioner Monti, must adopt a tough austerity package called for by the Europoliticians in order to regain the weak confidence in Italy.
The pressure to hurry, which weighs on Monti, was compounded by the fluctuating market situation, as a result of which Italian government bonds were charged with interest rates of 7% for 10 years, corresponding to the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to apply for the European bailout.
