The Italian association of foreign banks is also putting pressure on Monti's failure.
Monti began on Monday with his debates with political parties, trade unions and business associations, as well as with youth and women's organisations.
The session is scheduled to be completed on Tuesday evening.
Monti was appointed this Sunday by Napolitano, who set in motion an extremely rapid change of government in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite towards the end of the last week, when it became known that Berlusconi would resign, the uncertainty about the success of the new Prime Minister has brought the costs of Italian government bonds back to critical limits.
Saving Italy with a sovereign debt of 1.8 trillion euros would be too much for the current EU bailout umbrella.
