Some of the greatest shows we've done in the last 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We played on some giant shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that they have made us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
Really, we want to play there.
We love this country, we like surfing and we love the jungle. Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world for this.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
Many of our friends are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo, where the waves are simply unimaginable.
My friends have always gone surfing to Costa Rica and Nicaragua. Together with Mexico these are excellent areas for surfing. In this way, we have learned about people who love surfing.
With a look at the tour you have offered huge shows with many songs.
What plans do you have for the event in Costa Rica?
Since we have never played there, we set no limits.
We will try to give the best possible show with many different songs. We want to play a few songs from each album and offer our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
Why?
I think that's partly because we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs. Everyone likes a different song, so that the decision we're going to play is not easy.
If we record two or three songs that we haven't played for a long time in the repertoire, we can maintain our concentration better and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked these songs. Otherwise they might be forgotten.
This makes the show more interesting for us and I think that's why it's also for the audience.
With this tour you celebrate your twenty-year history.
When you look back, do you find it hard to believe in your success?
Yeah, totally.
First of all, I think that none of us imagined playing in a great rock band for over 20 years, which seems like a dream.
We also continue to rely on this blessing and find it great to be able to make music together even now.
We like each other and are enthusiastic about producing music.
We are lucky to be able to go to the places in the world that we have always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't stand better.
What did it mean for you to have actively participated in the birth of the Grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of big bands.
We are good friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and abundantly unusual when a movement emerges from a group of friends.
Every now and then, a band emerges from a city, but it is quite unusual when five or ten groups come from the same city at the same time.
We are proud of it and are honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on their tour. We are still looking forward to being friends with them all and it honors us to be part of this emerging Seattle sound.
It is also very unusual that a band like yours has stayed together with the same musicians for so long.
Yes, four of us have been playing together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) came to us 13 years ago. That alone is much more time than many bands survive.
First of all, I believe that we all appreciate being happy to be alive and we also take care of each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical paths have opened up, giving each individual the freedom to experiment.
One trusts the other and his music. We couldn't be better.
Your relationship to fame has not always been easy. On the other hand, thanks to your success, you could always do what you wanted.
How do you find balance?
The way we grew has made it easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure we don't go on tour too often, because it's too easy to fall for this game with huge crowds of people who love your music.
As long as you think people have come for the music, it reminds you that you have to pay attention to the music and what it has created, without being obsessed with being a famous rock star. We never cared about that anyway.
What memories do you have of your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote very good songs and at the beginning it was great.
We were a band for three years that had never released a record until Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
We were disappointed to have taken so long. We are still good with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who set up the band with us, friends. When I hear a song or see photos, I think about what an incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh. It was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh together and talk about music and football and many other topics.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The domestic band Las Robertas are responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose the band for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos from several groups and we liked this band best. That's why we are curious to see what Las Robertas can offer live.
Why do you always change Yellow Ledbetter's lyrics when you play live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), I have no idea.
He sings it, and I think he sings the first thing he can think of.
Who influenced you as a bass player?
Of so many+
The first ones I can think of are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk about the bassists I like all afternoon.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge alive, even though it is no longer a fashion phenomenon?
I think we all don't feel very connected with the word grunge.
When I think about it, I think of the bands I mentioned before, such as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and everyone else who came up at the same time. If they are still important today, I think that's great, because it's worth listening to this music and bands like Mudhoney are now making better music than ever before.
At first, her music was darker, now it's more positive.
Why?
That's interesting, because I think there are some songs on the new album that might seem a bit careless, but there are other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, although they also have something positive about them.
The tears came to me when I heard Ed play them. They are very dark songs.
I think if you get older and something traumatic has happened in your life - e.g. if you lose a family member or a friend - that will definitely affect your artistic work and your music and these two songs.
But I also believe that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
