The secretary, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, gives details of the aircraft accident, in which the government secretary Francisco Blake and another seven people were killed.
The Secretaría de Comunicaciones y Transport - SCT (Secretariat for Communications and Transport in Mexico) informed that the results of the investigation of the accident, in which the government secretary Francisco Blake Mora and another seven people were killed, pointed out that the helicopter, with its whole intact structure, had hit the ground directly without the pilot being able to launch an emergency landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, said that the pilot had confirmed before taking off that the weather conditions were suitable for the flight.
"The fact that the propeller wings had contact with trees at a height of 25 metres, with the helicopter losing its hull, seems to indicate that the helicopter had several ground contacts."
He also explained that the helicopter was built for 19 passengers, which is why it met all the requirements for the transport of personnel.
He also said that no helicopter parts were found during the investigations in the area where the machine had run down.
"In the search no aircraft parts were found in other places, the impact concerned the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 passengers, which is why it met all the requirements for passenger transport.
The area has an angle of 7 to 30 degrees.
At present, it is a priority to obtain the results of the investigation as soon as possible, but it may take several months, perhaps even a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Secretariat for Aircraft and Assistance Services in Mexico), assured that the helicopter had flown from the Estado Mayor Presidencial at cruising speed and that the plane had fallen on a soft slope.
"This information strengthens the assumption that it was a normal flight operation at the time of impact."
At a press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant points which should be taken into account in the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with the flight standards, it was a flight according to the rules of the visual flight. This means that the crew must have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded suitable weather conditions during take-off. During the onward flight towards the border area between Mexico City and the Mexico State, some low-hanging clouds were raised.
Selected flight routes:
It is possible that the crew had chosen a lower area with a better view towards the Cuernavaca valley because of the clouds.
Impact point:
The impact coordinates and the last radar recording of the helicopter match. Possibly there was no loss of control over the aircraft or a deviation from the flight route before the impact.
Dispersion of the remains of the aircraft in a limited area:
The information available to date indicates that the helicopter had bounced from a straight and lateral direction.
The pattern of scattered aircraft remains suggests that the helicopter, with its intact structure, had hit the ground.
No evidence of fire or explosion:
The remains of the aircraft offer at the scene of the accident do not indicate fire or explosion.
The last results of the investigation indicate several ground contacts.
During the on-site investigations, aircraft parts were found at an altitude of 9200 feet above sea level. The terrain is steep and has an angle of seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter was probably broken.
Some information suggests that the helicopter may have had several ground contacts.
After a meticulous search in an area beyond the closed area at the scene of the accident, no scattered parts of the aircraft could be found, which reinforces the assumption that the intact aircraft structure had hit the ground.
MSS announces a research protocol to find the gene for obesity
She is head of a research project on finding the gene for obesity in children and adolescents, supported by specialists from the IPN.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Social Insurance Institute of Mexico) announced that it is conducting a research project on the discovery of the gene for obesity in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of Obesity in Childhood and Adolescence", with which the genetic markers are to be found in connection with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, Head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Department of Medical Research, Focus on Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, stated that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was established.
This team is supported by specialists and students from the postgraduate programme at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested parties can come to the sports fields of the IMSS in the valley of Mexico, where tests with children and adolescents are conducted every Saturday from 8.00 a.m.
He stressed that the investigation began on the Cuauhtémoc sports field (in the west of the state of México) and continued on the sports field of Nezahualcóyolt (in the east of the state of México) since 8 October.
Once the target of 500 to 600 investigators has been achieved, the study will be continued on the sports field of Independencia (in the south of the capital district) and completed on that of Morelos (in the north of the capital district).
He explained that the aim of the study was to learn about the factors and role of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors for Mexican children and adolescents to prevent chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the global Day of Diabetes, he said that three thousand children and adolescents between the ages of six and 14 should complete nutrition-related questionnaires with the consent and supervision of their parents.
They are also asked questions about their physical activity and their family history in order to control risk factors that could lead to diabetes or kidney failure.
He also stated that on the above-mentioned Saturdays the subjects were measured (weight, size, waist circumference), their blood pressure was controlled and blood values such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (testing the identification of genes related to childhood obesity).
Cruz López stressed that this study would be carried out in the light of the concern of health workers about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"The health surveys from 1999 and 2006 showed that in just under six years, the proportion of obese boys increased by 77 percent and that of the obese girls increased by 47 percent. Overweight also increased dramatically," said IMSS specialist.
He claimed that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the population of Mexico differed from that of other peoples.
He said that an (e) Mexican (in) average is 65 percent Indian-American, 30 percent European and 5 percent African, which is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
In general, he explained that the genetics of obesity are expressed in the inability to burn the excess of energy (calories) taken from us, so that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to the participants of the study would be a comprehensive study of the children, which would determine whether they had a degree of obesity or obesity.
It would even investigate the occurrence of dark skin folds in the neck and the inner arm (Akanthosis), which indicate the likelihood of metabolic disorders and diabetes in the pre-stage.
All information would be treated confidentially and communicated in writing to the parents by the doctors. Doctors will explain to the parents all measurement results and suggest lifestyle changes that are appropriate for the prevention of diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three basic factors that are responsible for obesity, obesity and other chronic diseases: lack of exercise, that is, lack of exercise in everyday life, spending most of the day in front of the TV and using means of transport, instead of walking short distances.
The high calorie intake, that is, an increased consumption of sugared beverages and carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) together with a high fat and protein intake as well as the genetics that will be analyzed in this research project.
Asphalt from UNAM prevents potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University of UNAM, develops polymer modified asphalts to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If attention were to be paid to the signs from the road surface, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 potholes if the rainy season broke out in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (city area of the valley of Mexico), Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the University of UNAM, warned and assured that if the laying and maintenance of the asphalt surface were to be done appropriately, the number of potholes would be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "Threat holes from a technical point of view", which he gave on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climate, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behaviour of the road surface and thus avoid potholes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound, one of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalt - and the other a low - the so-called maltene. Together they give the road surface its characteristic viscous behavior.
The toughness of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120°C it is very viscous and almost solid at 50°C, while at very low temperatures it becomes fragile.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," said the chemical engineer.
The researcher at the FQ noted that the streets of Mexico City had a majority of flexible road surfaces, consisting of six layers of material, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the top layers there is a wear layer of asphalt consisting of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single piece of this wear layer had been bathed in asphalt.
If the vehicles move on to it and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed," said the chemical engineer.
"Over the wear layer", he said, "a last layer is laid out, the so-called supporting layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, they need a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they have to create friction.
This road surface receives and distributes most of the forces, the supporting layer also requires an appropriate thickness and the material from which it is made must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to be considered, especially the water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes damp, water penetrates into the layer and comes out difficult again. This causes a softening of all layers of the road surface and as a result, the appearance of potholes.
When a pothole is formed," he said, "the top layer is first removed, while the wear layer is only affected afterwards. However, the damage does not occur immediately, but rather it is a process that should be maintained at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) stated that the vehicle load is another important cause of the occurrence of potholes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road surface must always be in proportion to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is complied with in order to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there were still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries, and with which the potholes could be repaired easily and without applying high temperatures.
