Thus was the work of the doctor who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A Lophoscopeist from Cali entered the story as the man who identified "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials plays a key role.
On November 4, last year, a Lophoscope of the Investigation Unit of the Procuratorate (CTI) from Cali as the man who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia - Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia) came in: "Alfonso Cano" by comparing the fingerprints.
Of the seven Lophoscopists in the CTI department, Eliazar González, a Puerto Tejada man who has been involved in criminal investigations for 21 years, had been on call this week.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in communities of Chocó, where he often spent five days in the jungle to reach the place where the bodies he was supposed to identify were located.
In 2000 he moved to Valle and, after completing the necessary courses, specialized in lophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin exposed to friction, i.e. the palms and feet.
During the week of use against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was advised to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
Friday night he flew by helicopter from Palmira to Cauca.
He knew that he was supposed to identify two bodies and that there was a suspicion that one of the men who led the oldest guerrilla in the world could be one. Therefore, he should take the ten-finger print-sheet of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he reached the place where the body was located with the most examiner, he could not identify it because of its physical appearance, which was not the least similar to the images he had seen in the mass media.
He had no beard, was dressed like a farmer in the area, had no glasses and was much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a plant cell and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the body to those on the print sheet.
He had seen correctly: It was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, this Puerto Tejada-born man was in charge of telling the Secretary of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was actually the head of the FARC.
Searching for traces
For a dactyloscope from Sijín in Cali, the appreciation given by President Juan Manuel Santos Eliazar González at a press conference on the use of "Cano" was very important.
Many people don't know our work.
Daktyloscopy is an exact science without error rate, which can be a key factor in the resolution of a crime.
Lophoscopists not only identify corpses, they also support investigations into murder and robbery and confirm the identity of the arrested persons.
When they are arrested, many offenders present false identification papers or they do not have one.
We'll take their fingerprints and find them in the database.
The researcher told us that he had to tear a piece of wall out of a house in case of a theft, because the thief had supported himself with his hand exactly at this point when he pulled out a safe stuffed with jewelry and money.
"Walls are difficult because their surfaces are unsuitable for fingerprinting, but in this case we were able to take the print of the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in several thefts," he recalled.
With the help of fingerprints, murder suspects can also be relieved or charged.
Recently, a dead man was found surrounded by liquor bottles.
In the investigation, it was suspected that a family member might be suspected of being a suspect, and in fact, a fingerprint on the bottle coincided.
Although this does not guarantee that it is the murderer, it is linked to the place where the crime was committed.
A daktyloscopeist of the CTI explained that "the fingerprints with chemical or physical reagents are taken from the object."
When they appear, a plant cell or ribbon is used to carry them.
After that, the prints are sent to Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the civil status office.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians without ID papers," the expert from the CTI explained.
He said not everything was the way it was shown in the TV series SCI.
Just as not all gold is shining, not all you touch is a fingerprint.
But it can still be used if you make a corresponding comparison.
