Energy policy:
Facts Should Win Over Dogms
If an issue exists that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or emotions, this is certainly energy policy.
Availability and costs of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is reasonable to take an election meeting as an opportunity to reflect on this issue and on the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only bear fruit if it explores the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on this planet, demographic evolution is pushing for a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, a huge proportion of the world's population should not have to give up a vital element.
At the same time, the shortage of fossil resources must be mitigated in order to continue to produce electricity continuously, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate, in order to combat climatic irregularities.
The Fukushima accident does not alter any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is not the case in Belgium, which submits its decision to the need to find a substitutional source, nor in Switzerland, which only intends to build nuclear power plants of the last generation.
The UK, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name just a few, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
The United States, for its part, decided to join its park in Fukushima by reopening the Three Mile Island plant, which was closed after the nuclear accident.
Although the German model, which is geared to renewable energy sources, is sometimes presented as a model, the reality contradicts the discourse.
The election in Berlin will result in an increase in the price of electricity, an increase in energy dependence, especially on Russia, as a result of the increased use of imported gas, an increase in CO2 emissions caused by gas and coal power plants.
The totality of these unpleasant effects will become apparent within a few months.
The case of Denmark gives rise to reflection.
Denmark is, on the one hand, the European leader in the table for wind energy, from which it receives 30% of its electricity, and, on the other hand, the country is one of the strongest users of coal and gas, alternately used with wind energy, which means that its CO2 emissions and electricity prices are 65% and 50% higher than the corresponding European average.
Thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay 40% higher electricity bills than our French households.
Since the price of energy in the globalised economy is a key factor in competitiveness and a stability of industry on national soil, French companies have an advantage because of the most favourable electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore result in a strong increase in the price of energy, which would make the noble statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power an illusion.
Surveys showed that this is a price that the large majority of French people are just as unwilling to pay as it shows resistance to the principle of this energy source.
Let us remember that our country's energy policy has made it possible to build an industry with 125.00 direct and 410,000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export character, it brings a large number of specialised small and medium-sized enterprises to the international markets and makes them creators of countless jobs.
If France took the decision to phase out nuclear power, a large part of these SMEs would fall victim to it, and the EUR 6 billion in capital goods and nuclear energy exports per year would shrink more and more.
Which electrician would commission an EPR designed to function for sixty years if the decline of his producer is pre-programmed?
In order to solve the energetic equation one has to admit that there is as little as a devil's work a miracle remedy for the generation of electricity.
The low-carbon solutions developed by Areva for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy demonstrate the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a safety authority that carries out uncompromising and transparent controls in existing plants, such as the Flamanville construction site.
Their work teams, who have made a name for themselves because of their professionalism, are just too obsessed with the concept of security.
Within 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious incidents.
Only one, and that in Three Mile Island, has occurred under normal operating conditions, so it has been without consequences for man and the environment.
In Chernobyl, the drama was evoked by reactor construction and inexcusable human failure.
At Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters, which caused the deaths of several tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will draw its lessons from this accident as it had done after the two previous ones.
As a result of this approach as well as a cooperation between the safety authorities of the French and German operators and constructors of nuclear power plants, the EPR represents a draft that enables it to withstand such phenomena.
Since it is considered desirable for electrical engineers to build a nuclear power plant, a stop in Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the competition of Areva and EDF by allowing them to take the lead in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is imperative and legitimate to seek the best energy bouquet for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow emotions, dogmas and party manoeuvres to dominate a debate that also determines our country's economic, social and financial situation.
