But this policy has rarely been analysed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus on this issue between the right and the left.
On the right side, the tone of Jacques Chirac was struck, who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed, including more than 2 million immigrated workers, should not be a problem for a country" from the left, by Michel Rocard, who stated in 1990 that France "could not absorb all the poverty of the world".
The only difference is in the degree of largeness
The fear of the invasion of national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was divided in 2005 from both right and left.
Both camps saw immigrants as a burden for the economy and French society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity one is willing to admit to immigrants.
Francois Hollande's programme confines himself to banalities that point to partnership development allowing us to solve our "migration problems".
This notion of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may have an impact on the elections, but it is economically costly.
As the economic experts Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron remind us in a recent work that summarizes the latest insights on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.), there is a broad consensus among the specialists on the positive impact of the immigration flood on economic growth, wages and jobs in the immigration countries.
Restricting immigration would depress growth and damage the labour market situation.
The fears about the influence of migrants are based on the idea that they threaten to substitute the domestic workforce, especially the less skilled, by exerting pressure on their wages.
Experience shows, however, that immigrants are, in fact, much more complementary than local wage earners, as they focus on occupations in sectors that are jobless in terms of employment.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors where domestic wage workers are less incentivised, the more skilled of immigrants work in dynamic sectors where training is not aligned with labour supply.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would find it difficult to work in a country where there is a lack of anesthesiologists, so this complementarity between locals and migrants also has a positive effect on wages and the domestic labour market situation.
Giovanni Peri has calculated in this way that a 1% increase in the immigration flood would result in a related, long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity of ideas introduced by immigrants is beneficial to the creation of ideas and economic growth (high proportion of native immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also make a net contribution to social security systems, with an average of about 1% of the total budget in European countries.
