Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects Western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is said to supply gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with splendor and glory.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Russia and Germany directly below sea level.
German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte symbolically turned together the control of the valve that transports the Russian gas into the Western European network.
With the new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas per year will be delivered to Western Europe through a first 1.224 km pipeline connecting the St Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania.
A second pipeline, which allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic metres of gas - the equivalent of the total French consumption - is to be completed by the end of 2012.
And you can already mention the eventuality of building a third line on your own track.
For Gazprom, the timely and accurate completion of this enormous building looks like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord-Stream pipeline will enable a direct gas supply to Germany, avoiding any route through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) by land.
For this reason, these two countries lose a little of their power: for them, it is becoming more difficult to exert pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most heavily engaged in the debate, was not afraid to compare the North Stream pipeline with a "new German-Soviet pact" linked to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the purpose of the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the topic is politically extremely sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by supporting this Russian project.
This, however, at the expense of defusing European energy, as the project has broken the gap between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In barely five years' time, Russia has managed to enforce its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, western countries that have strong gas consumptions and whose gas reserves are running out.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way," confirmed François Fillon at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out to what extent the major gas contracts are also important from the political and economic point of view.
All this explains the broad smile of the numerous Gazprom managers represented in Lubmin regarding the gas supply line.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater line is made of steel with concrete sheathing, which is intended to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea at a depth of about 200 metres.
During its construction, minefields dating from the Second World War had to be evaded.
"About hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, stronger measures to protect fauna and flora had to be taken.
The line is a long snake made of metal, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which is interrupted over the entire length by nothing: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers have refrained from it, as the Swedes had little desire to see a Russian state society settle in a permanent way at the level of their coasts.
"In the event of a disaster, we close the gas outlet in less than a minute," said Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered to be unlikely by the constructors, since the seams were estimated to be resistant to one leak per 100,000 years.
State surveillance of the gas pipeline is ensured both by an underwater robot controlled for external observation purposes by a seagoing vessel and by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, with a diameter of one meter, is inserted into the inside of the pipe and moved through the gas pressure.
After three full days of moving through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on its arrival about possible deformations of the metal.
The gas pipeline has been designed to function for fifty years without having to undergo even the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entrance, 100 bar at the exit.
Five societies have joined forces to realize this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E. ON and BASF are affiliated here (each 15.5%), as are the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (each 9%).
These five companies have formed a group of companies called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire capacity of its gas transport to this company on a renewable twenty-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the real-transported gas volume is," said Jens Müller.
The financing of the gas pipeline was secured by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
Total labour costs should amount to 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amount was 240 million.
However, minority shareholders are aware that they will recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the risk of liability.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea on a sandy, pine-wooded coastline near Lubmin.
The 4.5-meter-high valves form the gas outlet gates.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other key figures of the incoming gas before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with one million cubic metres of Russian gas per passing hour.
With full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic metres per hour and 6 million in 2012.
